 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tachyon Wrangler</span><br>  Posts: 214<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/27/03 6:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/images/offedge.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay</span><hr size=1> As a general thought...<br>
<br>
What would the inclusion of a &quot;Deadman&quot; system imply fer a rocket/booster/spacecraft..?<br>
<br>
That is, a purely mechanical system that would seal the reactor (entire spacecraft..?) off, in the event of a pressure/power failure..<br>
<br>
Something designed to kick in and seal off the system iff'n every other controlling system fails..a process that loss of computer and power and hydraulics would not effect..?<br>
<br>
This could be implemented with a crew escape system..or with a mind towards &quot;avoid the fallout and sacrifice the few to preserve the many&quot; viewpoint...<br>
<br>
In essence, turn the failed craft into a heavily sealed and shielded container that, to the best of our ability, is impervious to the rigors of re-entry and impact...<br>
<br>
I don't see this as being particularly difficult to achieve, considering our current level of engineering and technology...tho, the added weight of a proper shielding system might be prohibitive to launch capability, atm...<br>
<br>
Comments..? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.whitetoweronline.com"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.whitetoweronline.com/hall/icons/barth-sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sovin>Sovin</A> at: 7/27/03 6:59 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1335<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/27/03 10:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=348.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Okay</span><hr size=1> That is the &quot;Rube Goldberg&quot; system that would most likely NOT be available when needed.<br>
<br>
Remember, the &quot;light bulb&quot; GCNR uses special giant glass cylinders containing fearsomely radioactive GASES at 100,000 degrees or so, located in an open thrust chamber with giant open nozzles.<br>
<br>
Consider as a scenario an event which has already occured in an arianne launch.<br>
<br>
A software glich causes the computers to throw the rocket out of control - MUCH MUCH faster than a human could respond to. The rocket tumbles out of control - being instanly torn apart by aerodynamic forces. The thrust chambers - minus any functioning control power, or working equipment hurtle any number of thousands of miles til they impact - where?<br>
<br>
As I posted earlier - responsible engineering design requires that you assume that none of the protective mechanisms would be available - which is a quite reasonable position.<br>
<br>
<br>
